  "prompt": "What's the difference between buffered I/O and unbuffered I/O?",
  "response": "Let me explain the key differences between buffered and unbuffered I/O:\n\nBuffered I/O:\n1. Uses an intermediate memory buffer\n2. Reduces number of system calls\n3. More efficient for larger data transfers\n4. Data is collected in memory before actual I/O operation\n5. Default mode for most standard I/O operations\n6. Examples: \n   - stdio functions like fread(), fwrite()\n   - Python's file.read(), file.write()\n   - Java's BufferedReader, BufferedWriter\n\nPros:\n- Improved performance\n- Reduced overhead\n- Smoother data transfer\n\nCons:\n- Slight memory overhead\n- Potential delay in data writing\n\nUnbuffered I/O:\n1. Direct system calls for each I/O operation\n2. Immediate read/write to/from device\n3. Lower-level, more direct access\n4. Less overhead for small, infrequent transfers\n5. Examples:\n   - Low-level system calls like read(), write()\n   - C's raw file operations\n   - Direct file descriptor operations\n\nPros:\n- Immediate data transfer\n- Less memory usage\n- More precise control\n\nCons:\n- Less efficient for large transfers\n- More system call overhead\n- Potentially slower performance\n\nExample in Python:\n```python\n# Buffered I/O\nwith open('file.txt', 'r') as f:\n    data = f.read()  # Buffered\n\n# Unbuffered I/O\nimport os\nfd = os.open('file.txt', os.O_RDONLY)\ndata = os.read(fd, 1024)  # Unbuffered\nos.close(fd)\n```\n\nChoose based on specific performance and precision requirements.",
